---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

// Tenant-mix comparison (Finding 4) rendered as an accessible table.
const mixRows: { measure: string; south: string; east: string }[] = [
  { measure: 'Retail goods', south: '41%', east: '21%' },
  { measure: 'Professional services', south: '1%', east: '11%' },
  { measure: 'Health and fitness', south: '6%', east: '8%' },
  { measure: 'Grocery and fresh food', south: '3%', east: '5%' },
  { measure: 'Peaks late at night', south: '23%', east: 'under 1%' },
  { measure: 'Smoke shops and check-cashers', south: '9%', east: '0%' },
  { measure: 'Value-priced (mean tier, 1 to 4)', south: '1.96', east: '2.39' },
  { measure: 'Outdoor seating', south: '7%', east: '20%' },
];
---

<Layout title="Findings · Saving South Street">
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <!-- HERO -->
    <section>
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-stone-900">Findings</h1>
      <p class="finding-headline">South Street's decline is structural, not ambient.</p>
      <p class="mt-3 text-stone-700">
        A 2026 storefront-by-storefront survey of the corridor, measured against East Passyunk
        Avenue.
      </p>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm">
        <a
          href="/thesis.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener"
          class="text-stone-500 underline underline-offset-2 hover:text-stone-800"
        >Read the full chapter (PDF)</a>
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- EXECUTIVE SUMMARY -->
    <section class="finding-section">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-stone-900">Executive summary</h2>
      <p class="finding-body">
        South Street's emptiness gets blamed on COVID and e-commerce. This study tests that with a
        2026 field survey of every storefront on the corridor, measured against East Passyunk Avenue,
        a peer with the same pre-1900 building stock, the same density and transit, and a
        wealthier-than-average neighborhood. East Passyunk faced the same retail pressure and stayed
        full. South Street did not. The decline is structural to the corridor, not ambient to retail.
      </p>
      <ul class="finding-stats">
        <li><strong>A 17-point occupancy gap.</strong> South Street runs 70.3% occupied against East Passyunk's 87.3%.</li>
        <li><strong>Half the vacancy is frozen.</strong> Of 68 empty storefronts, 35 are long-term vacant, against just 2 on East Passyunk. The emptiness is stuck, not turning over.</li>
        <li><strong>Three in five parcels sit with dormant owners.</strong> 155 of 271 parcels have either changed hands without a market sale or not sold in over 20 years.</li>
        <li><strong>Prices climb while the buildings rot.</strong> South Street land sells for about 1.8 times East Passyunk's, a $273,000 premium, even as half its parcels logged a new code violation in the last three years, four times East Passyunk's count.</li>
        <li><strong>The mix flipped, not the ownership.</strong> Both corridors are about 87% independent, so chains are a myth. South Street skews value-priced, late-night, and takeout, with smoke shops and check-cashers at 9.4% of tenants versus zero, and it runs thin on daytime, fitness, and fresh-food uses.</li>
        <li><strong>The culture economy hollowed out.</strong> The corridor that ran on live music, comedy, and galleries is down to one surviving venue, the TLA. The Laff House, where Kevin Hart and Bill Burr started, closed in 2013 with no comedy club since, and a third of the corridor's anchor parcels, several of them former venues, sit empty.</li>
        <li><strong>The damage concentrates on a few blocks.</strong> The Front-to-5th dead zone carries the worst of it. The 300 block alone is 59% vacant, while the western 900 and 1000 blocks outperform East Passyunk.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- FINDING 1 -->
    <section class="finding-section">
      <p class="finding-kicker">Finding 1</p>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-stone-900">The occupancy gap</h2>
      <p class="finding-stat">
        South Street runs 70.3% occupied. East Passyunk runs 87.3%. A 17-point gap.
      </p>
      <p class="finding-body">
        East Passyunk sits on the same pre-1900 building stock, the same density, and the same
        transit, and it faced the same retail pressure. It stayed full. South Street did not.
      </p>
      <p class="finding-body">
        The deeper story is the kind of vacancy, not just the amount. South Street has 68 empty
        storefronts and 35 of them are long-term vacant. East Passyunk has 20 empty and only 2 are
        long-term. Half of South Street's emptiness is sitting still, not turning over.
      </p>
      <p class="finding-body">
        A storefront counts as long-term vacant when it shows no sign of a next tenant: no for-rent
        sign, no posted permit, no visible work inside, and visible neglect like rotted trim, leaks,
        and faded graffiti. In plain terms, it could not appear on a brokerage listing today.
      </p>

      <figure class="finding-figure">
        <img
          src="/images/Figure%205.6.webp"
          alt="Bar chart comparing commercial occupancy rates: South Street 70.3 percent, East Passyunk 87.3 percent."
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
        />
        <figcaption>
          <span class="finding-caption">
            Commercial occupancy rate on South Street and East Passyunk.
          </span>
          <span class="finding-source">
            Source: Author's field survey, 2026. Sample restricted to parcels with commercial real
            estate space (South Street n=229; East Passyunk n=157).
          </span>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>

      <figure class="finding-figure">
        <img
          src="/images/Figure%205.7.webp"
          alt="Chart comparing vacancy type composition on South Street and East Passyunk, showing South Street's larger share of long-term vacancy."
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
        />
        <figcaption>
          <span class="finding-caption">
            Vacancy type composition on South Street and East Passyunk.
          </span>
          <span class="finding-source">
            Source: Author's field survey, 2026. Sample restricted to vacant commercial parcels
            (South Street n=68; East Passyunk n=20).
          </span>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </section>

    <!-- FINDING 2 -->
    <section class="finding-section">
      <p class="finding-kicker">Finding 2</p>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-stone-900">
        Dormant owners hold the land while the buildings wait
      </h2>
      <p class="finding-stat">
        155 of South Street's 271 parcels, about three in five, have either changed hands for a
        dollar or not sold in over 20 years. The land sells for about 1.8 times East Passyunk's, a
        $273,000 premium.
      </p>
      <p class="finding-body">
        A parcel carries two values, the land underneath and the building on top. When an owner is
        engaged, running the storefront and maintaining the building, both values rise together. When
        an owner is dormant, holding for land appreciation instead of operating income, the two split
        apart. That split is South Street's diagnosis.
      </p>
      <p class="finding-body">
        Society Hill and Queen Village, two of the highest-income neighborhoods in the city, sit on
        either side of the corridor and set a price floor under the land. Center City is a 15-minute
        walk away. Together they price the parcels on what they could become, housing or mixed-use,
        not on how the storefront performs today. So an owner can leave a storefront empty, keep
        collecting rent from the apartments above, and still watch the land appreciate. Holding
        without operating becomes the rational move.
      </p>
      <p class="finding-body">
        East Passyunk never had that price floor. When PARC and its predecessor began buying there,
        the land was cheap enough to acquire ten parcels and tie rents to tenant sales. South Street
        never had a group buy the bricks. Its long holds belong to portfolio owners like Axelrod and
        Midwood, who together control more than 40 addresses, concentrated on the eastern blocks where
        vacancy runs heaviest.
      </p>

      <figure class="finding-figure">
        <img
          src="/images/Figure%205.4.webp"
          alt="Chart of the distribution of years since last sale for South Street and East Passyunk parcels."
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
        />
        <figcaption>
          <span class="finding-caption">
            Distribution of years since last sale on South Street and East Passyunk parcels.
          </span>
          <span class="finding-source">
            Source: Author's analysis of Philadelphia Office of Property Assessment records.
            CMX-zoned parcels with valid sale-date records (South Street n=235 of 245; East Passyunk
            n=196 of 196).
          </span>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </section>

    <!-- FINDING 3 -->
    <section class="finding-section">
      <p class="finding-kicker">Finding 3</p>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-stone-900">
        The buildings are decaying in motion
      </h2>
      <p class="finding-stat">
        Half of South Street's CMX parcels (50.2%) logged a new code violation in the last three
        years. That is four times East Passyunk's rate.
      </p>
      <p class="finding-body">
        This is the building half of the land-value split. The deterioration is not leftover from a
        past decade. It is happening now, while prices stay high.
      </p>
      <p class="finding-body">
        South Street's violation profile runs higher than East Passyunk's at every level of severity,
        and 16.2% of its parcels carry an open violation today. Owners are letting the buildings slide
        even as the parcels gain value.
      </p>

      <figure class="finding-figure">
        <img
          src="/images/Figure%205.5.webp"
          alt="Chart of code violation severity and recent activity for South Street and East Passyunk parcels."
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
        />
        <figcaption>
          <span class="finding-caption">
            Code violation severity and recent activity on South Street and East Passyunk parcels.
          </span>
          <span class="finding-source">
            Source: Author's analysis of Philadelphia Office of Property Assessment records and
            Licenses and Inspections violation history. CMX-zoned parcels (South Street n=245; East
            Passyunk n=196). The recent count reflects parcels with a most recent violation dated on
            or after January 1, 2023.
          </span>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </section>

    <!-- FINDING 4 -->
    <section class="finding-section">
      <p class="finding-kicker">Finding 4</p>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-stone-900">
        The mix flipped, not the ownership
      </h2>
      <p class="finding-stat">
        Both corridors are about 87% independent. The story that national chains killed South Street
        is a myth.
      </p>
      <p class="finding-body">
        What changed is what the independent storefronts sell and when they open. South Street leans
        value-priced, late-night, and takeout. Smoke shops and check-cashers make up 9.4% of its
        tenants and zero of East Passyunk's. It runs thin on the daily-life uses that hold a
        neighborhood: professional services, fitness, and fresh food.
      </p>

      <div class="finding-table-wrap">
        <table class="finding-table">
          <caption class="finding-table-caption">
            Tenant mix on South Street compared with East Passyunk.
          </caption>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th scope="col">Measure</th>
              <th scope="col">South Street</th>
              <th scope="col">East Passyunk</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {mixRows.map((row) => (
              <tr>
                <th scope="row">{row.measure}</th>
                <td>{row.south}</td>
                <td>{row.east}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="finding-source finding-source--table">
        Source: Author's field survey, 2026. Active CMX tenants (South Street n=160; East Passyunk
        n=132).
      </p>

      <p class="finding-body">
        East Passyunk packs about 80% of its tenants into the afternoon and evening, the hours that
        serve a neighborhood. South Street tilts late-night and in-and-out. The mid-day to
        early-evening economy is what is missing.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- FINDING 5 -->
    <section class="finding-section">
      <p class="finding-kicker">Finding 5</p>
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-stone-900">
        The damage concentrates on a few blocks
      </h2>
      <p class="finding-stat">
        The 300 block is 59% vacant, 23 of 39 storefronts empty, more than the next three worst blocks
        combined. The western 900 and 1000 blocks, at 12% and 11%, beat East Passyunk's 12.7%.
      </p>
      <p class="finding-body">
        South Street's 30% corridor average is propped up almost entirely by the 300 block. Take it
        out and the other ten blocks come in at 24%. The healthy western end is healthier than the
        comparison corridor.
      </p>
      <p class="finding-body">
        The 300 block alone holds 14 of the corridor's 35 long-term vacant parcels, 40% of the stuck
        inventory on a single block.
      </p>

      <figure class="finding-figure">
        <img
          src="/images/Figure%205.8.webp"
          alt="Bar chart of commercial vacancy rate by block on South Street, with the 300 block as a clear outlier."
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
        />
        <figcaption>
          <span class="finding-caption">
            Commercial vacancy rate by block on South Street, 2026.
          </span>
          <span class="finding-source">
            Source: Author's 2026 field survey. Vacancy rate per block calculated as the share of
            commercial parcels currently vacant (n=229). The 300 block is the corridor's vacancy
            outlier.
          </span>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>

      <aside class="finding-callout">
        <img
          class="finding-callout-img"
          src="/images/tla-marquee.png"
          alt="The Theatre of the Living Arts marquee on South Street, the corridor's last surviving live venue."
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
        />
        <div class="finding-callout-body">
          <h3 class="finding-callout-title">The dead zone is where the culture used to be.</h3>
          <p>
            The Front-to-5th stretch that now reads as a ghost town is the same ground that once held
            the corridor's live entertainment cluster: music halls, jazz rooms, and comedy clubs.
            South Street built its name on that scene.
          </p>
          <p>
            Today it is down to one surviving venue, the Theatre of the Living Arts. Ripley's Music
            Hall closed in 1985, Grendel's Lair in 1987, and JC Dobbs in 1996. The Laff House, where
            Kevin Hart and Bill Burr started out, closed in 2013, and no comedy club has replaced it
            in the 13 years since.
          </p>
          <p>
            By the 2026 survey, arts and culture had fallen to 4.4% of the corridor's active tenants,
            a steep drop for a street that once ran on performance. A third of South Street's anchor
            parcels, nine of twenty-seven, sit empty, several of them former venues.
          </p>
        </div>
      </aside>
    </section>

    <!-- HANDOFF -->
    <section class="finding-section">
      <p class="finding-handoff-lead">
        These findings are the evidence. What they mean, and what to do about them, lives on the next
        two tabs.
      </p>
      <ul class="finding-handoff-list">
        <li>
          <a href="/analysis">The Policy Analysis tab</a> traces the three problems behind the numbers
          and lays out four proposals.
        </li>
        <li><a href="/map">The Map</a> shows the survey parcel by parcel.</li>
        <li>
          The full Chapter V, with every figure and table, is in the
          <a href="/thesis.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">thesis</a>.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </div>
</Layout>

<style>
